    <segment id="1" parent="2" relname="background">
I am glad to say I am finally caught up with all the reading.</segment>
    <segment id="2" parent="24" relname="span"> After reading all the assigned chapters and articles, something hit me.</segment>
    <segment id="3" parent="26" relname="span"> We talk about all these terms to support the importance of user-friendliness, user-centered and so forth.</segment>
    <segment id="4" parent="32" relname="span"> I have observed through my mother</segment>
    <segment id="29" parent="4" relname="circumstance"> (I recently bought her a computer)</segment>
    <segment id="30" parent="31" relname="same-unit"> a new user, a novice or a new computer experiencer.</segment>
    <segment id="5" parent="28" relname="span"> I, on the hand, grew up with computers,</segment>
    <segment id="11" parent="18" relname="span"> my 1st grade class had an Apple 2E and we played sneakers on it;</segment>
    <segment id="12" parent="11" relname="elaboration"> I even learned basic.</segment>
    <segment id="6" parent="19" relname="contrast"> 
My generation is significantly smaller then hers.</segment>
    <segment id="7" parent="19" relname="contrast"> In regards to business her generation has more value and more disposable cash.</segment>
    <segment id="8" parent="21" relname="span"> However, computer technology has created 2 kinds of users:</segment>
    <segment id="13" parent="33" relname="contrast"> me, who is experienced</segment>
    <segment id="20" parent="37" relname="span"> and her that is scare</segment>
    <segment id="34" parent="35" relname="condition"> if she hits the wrong button</segment>
    <segment id="35" parent="36" relname="span"> we will have World War III on our hands.</segment>
    <segment id="9" parent="22" relname="span"> 
My point is that her kind of user is completely ignored, the terms listed:</segment>
    <segment id="15" parent="9" relname="elaboration"> ease of use ease of learning or learnabililty efficiency memorability error recovery user satisfaction flexibility consistency </segment>
    <segment id="14" parent="23" relname="solutionhood">
Who are they for, me or her or both?</segment>
    <segment id="10" parent="23" relname="span"> In my opinion she and those inexperienced users are ignored</segment>
    <segment id="16" parent="10" relname="elaboration"> and there is a lack of a model for those type users.</segment>
